1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Hello ! 

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Our planet is covered by 70 percent of the ocean, yet, oddly enough, we chose to call it Earth.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:12,000
The poet Heathcote Williams has a much more objective and less anthropocentric view, when he says that  From the view of space, the planet is blue.

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:16,000
From the perspective of space, it is the territory, not of men, but of whales.

5
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:20,000
And yet, we all come from the ocean.

6
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:24,000
It is the cradle of life, even if it is forgotten.

7
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:28,000
The ocean is everywhere: in glaciers, rivers, watersheds, in the cells of living things, and in our veins.

8
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:32,000
Strangely enough, it was John Fitzgerald Kennedy who illustrated this quite well, in this quote:  It is an interesting biological fact that each one has in his veins an equal percentage of salt in his blood, to that in the oceans.

9
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:36,000
So we all have salt in our blood, sweat, and tears.

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:40,000
We are bound to the ocean, and when we return to the sea, whether to sail or to watch, we return to where we came from.

11
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:44,000
Yet this ocean is very, very little known.

12
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:48,000
It remains a rather strange and strange world, which is sometimes scary.

13
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:52,000
That said, in fact, it is far from an inert body of water, a stretch of water that is useless.

14
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
In fact, it is marine life that makes this ocean a major climate regulator, the main carbon well, and also, the main oxygen producer.

15
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Between 50 and 70 percent of the oxygen comes from the ocean.

16
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
So, in fact, more than one out of every two inspirations you take, you owe to the ocean.

17
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Not quite at sea!

18
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:12,000
In fact, you owe it to marine life.

19
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Marine life is what enables this mass of water, precisely, to be not just an inert mass of water, but to be that machine that enables us to live.

20
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:20,000
And marine life is part of the phytoplankton that supplies oxygen, to the great whales, to the great predators, thons, dolphins... And among these species, there are some that are more ecologically important than others, including sharks.

21
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:24,000
This is, therefore, the example I chose because it is an animal that we tend to demonize, a marine monster.

22
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Yet, every year, 70 million sharks are slaughtered.

23
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:32,000
It's as if the equivalent of France were being exterminated.

24
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Or, the sharks are the record-keepers of evolution.

25
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
They are 470 million years old.

26
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:44,000
This means that for 470 million years, all life in the ocean was shaped by, and according to, sharks.

27
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,000
And as a top predator, key-tail species, when you remove sharks from an ecosystem, you have a collapse of marine biodiversity.

28
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,000
So where the sharks disappeared, on a dead water, or on a jellyfish explosion, but there is no life left.

29
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Here you are!

30
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
That's the role of predators.

31
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:04,000
We, as humans, tend to consider ourselves the top predators.

32
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:08,000
And yet, we are far from predators, since, in Nature, predators are, on the one hand, regulated by the availability of their prey - or this is no longer the case for us since agriculture and livestock were invented - on the other hand, predators tend to not reproduce unless they reproduce.

33
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:12,000
So cheetahs or lions will have far fewer cubs than mice or rabbits.

34
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Mice and rabbits are prey, naturally, so they need to reproduce very quickly, and in very large numbers.

35
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Sharks, whales, dolphins, are predators.

36
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
They were not designed to be prey.

37
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:28,000
We have made them prey!

38
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:32,000
So they cannot, in fact, survive the predatory pressure of man.

39
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:36,000
There is also something in common with all these marine animals, whether predators or not.

40
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Because they all participate in marine life, that is, a life cycle, unlike us.

41
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:44,000
To give you an example of blue whales, a blue whale produces, every day, 3 tons of excrement - excrement that is very rich in nitrogen or nitrogen - and that, they are the essential nutrients for phytoplancton that provides us with the oxygen we breathe.

42
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,000
In fact, over the past 50 years, about 40% of the phytoplankton population has been lost, largely because whales were exterminated in the 20th century and before, but even more so with the invention of the explosive harpoon.

43
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:52,000
The man, however, went to sea.

44
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:56,000
It is not part of that ecosystem.

45
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:00,000
We are no longer part of it since we left the ocean.

46
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,000
So we are an intruder.

47
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
One is an intruder with fishing, predation, and now industrialized means.

48
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,000
And one is a predator that no longer has the natural limits of predators.

49
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
So we are over 7 billion, and today, 7 billion humans want to eat fish.

50
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
So that's a big problem.

